        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><persName role="author">MYER S. ISAACS</persName>,</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">Attorney &amp; <sic>Counsellor</sic> at Law.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">Notary Public,</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>243 BROADWAY, ROOMS 9 AND 10</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>, <date>Aug 27th 1868</date></p>
            <p>My dear sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The receipt of your note and<lb/> enclosed communication
                reminds<lb/> me that I had neglected acknowl<lb/>edging receipt of notice of meeting<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Josephi<add>?</add></persName> has gone to
                    <placeName>Europe</placeName>, it is<lb/> quite out of my power, I regret
                to<lb/> say to be with you on <date>Monday</date>. I<lb/> can't speak for
                    <persName>Mr. Sa<add>?</add></persName></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The article in the <hi rend="underline">Israelite</hi> is<lb/>
                scandalous — I had presumed an<lb/>
                <add>?</add> reply which is in the<lb/> Messenger. Yours of course is too late<lb/>
                this week (rec'd <date>Monday</date> at 10) but<lb/> it shall appear <hi
                    rend="underline">entire</hi>, I expect<lb/> next week with some remarks by<lb/>
                a “trustee.” While I feel that<lb/> this contemptible assault is in the<lb/>
                interest of men who fear their</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>“occupation will be gone” I <del>f</del><lb/> am as disgusted with our<lb/> orthodox
                brethren who are very<lb/> slow to appreciate the necessity<lb/> of Hebrew
                Education. You find<lb/> us of the <hi rend="underline">Messenger</hi>
                    working<add>?</add> pretty<lb/> steadily with the <hi rend="underline"
                    >Occident</hi> on this<lb/> question, but it is very, very<lb/>
                <add>?</add> work to get <hi rend="underline">money</hi> &amp;<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">pupils</hi></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You shall have 2 from <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> (2
                pupils) any others expected?<lb/> Please tell <persName>Mr Dropsie</persName> that
                I<lb/> have <sic>despatched</sic> his notes to our<lb/> leading congregations,
                with<lb/> more misgivings than hopes. We<lb/> must be unusually patient,<lb/> &amp;
                persevere with the college<lb/> notwithstanding our limited</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>success with the public.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I feel personally that I ought<lb/> not to be a trustee because I
                lack<lb/> the time &amp; means to push the<lb/> work of money-getting. I'll
                make<lb/> another effort these holydays.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Don't be worried by the<lb/> barking of the
                    <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName><lb/> hound. Its' characteristic. He<lb/> is
                coming to <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> to dedicate<lb/> a Temple. Perhaps he
                may<lb/> hear something to his advantage.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With kind regards to <persName>Mr<lb/> Dropsie</persName> &amp; the
                Gentlemen of the<lb/> College</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Truly yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">M S Isaacs</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>
                <persName role="author">M S Isaacs</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <date>Aug. 27/68</date>
            </p>
